
:: DirectTravelStrategy
<<set $step = 0>><<ShowInfo>><<set $day += 45>><<GenerateTimeSkipWorries 45>>

<h3>The Direct Service Model</h3>
<div class="consequence-text">
	<p>You make a decision: you'll position yourself as someone who provides direct, professional service. When clients call, you tell them: "I can come directly to your home. I'll bring all my tools. You won't have to worry about picking me up or coordinating."</p>
	<p>This differentiates you. Many informal workers can't offer this - they rely on clients picking them up, or they're limited by public transit. But you're willing to rideshare directly to each job.</p>
	<p>It's expensive. Most days you're taking 3-4 separate rideshares - to the first job, to the second, to the third, then home. At $18-25 per ride, that's $70-100 per day in transportation alone. Some days you spend $500+ per week just getting around.</p>
	<p>But the strategy has an advantage: clients who value convenience will pay more. And they refer you to other clients who value the same thing.</p>
	<p>"I know someone who needs painting done," a satisfied client tells their neighbor. "This guy will come directly to you. Very professional."</p>
	<p>You start getting called for jobs you wouldn't have access to otherwise. Homeowners who don't want to coordinate transportation. Small business owners who need someone reliable. People who are willing to pay extra for convenience.</p>
	<p>The question is: can you earn enough to make the rideshare costs worthwhile?</p>
</div> <hr>
<<link "See how it plays out">><<goto "DirectTravelProgress">><</link>>

:: DirectTravelProgress
<<set $step = 0>><<ShowInfo>><<set $day += 30>><<GenerateTimeSkipWorries 30>>

<h3>Two Months Later</h3>
<div class="consequence-text">
	<p>You've been running the direct travel model for two and a half months now. Every morning, you check your phone for job requests. You plan your route. You rideshare from job to job, carrying your toolbox, presenting yourself professionally.</p>
	<p>The costs have been significant. You're spending $400-600 per month on rideshares, just as you predicted. Some weeks it feels unsustainable.</p>
	<p>But the work has been good. You're getting referrals. Clients like that you show up on time, at their location, ready to work. Your phone rings more often than it used to.</p>
	<p>The question is whether the higher-paying jobs and referrals will offset the transportation costs - or whether you're just running in place, earning more but spending more, with no net progress.</p>
</div>
<hr>
<<set _directOutcome = random(1, 100)>>
<<if _directOutcome <= 50>>
	<<goto "DirectTravelFail">>
<<else>>
	<<goto "DirectTravelSuccess">>
<</if>>

:: DirectTravelFail
<<set $step = 0>><<ShowInfo>><<set $day += 30>><<GenerateTimeSkipWorries 30>>

<h3>Unsustainable Economics</h3>
<div class="consequence-text">
	<p>Three months in, you have to face the math.</p>
	<p>You're getting jobs. You're getting referrals. Clients are happy with your work. On the surface, the business model is working.</p>
	<p>But when you sit down and actually calculate the numbers, the reality is harsh:</p>
	<ul style="margin:8px 0;">
		<li>Average daily earnings: $180</li>
		<li>Average daily rideshare costs: $85</li>
		<li>Net daily income: $95</li>
		<li>Working 22 days per month: $2,090</li>
		<li>After rent ($<<= $housingCost>>): $<<= 2090 - $housingCost>> remaining</li>
	</ul>
	<p>That $<<= 2090 - $housingCost>> has to cover food for your family, unexpected expenses, everything else. There's no buffer. No savings. No progress toward a better situation.</p>
	<p>In fact, you realize you were doing better when you weren't spending so much on transportation. The higher-paying jobs and referrals sounded good, but they're not paying enough to offset the massive transportation costs.</p>
	<p>You're working just as hard as before, maybe harder, but you're not actually getting ahead. The rideshare companies are taking too much of your earnings.</p>
	<p>Worse, you're now dependent on this model. Your clients expect you to come directly to them. If you stop offering that service, you'll lose them. You're trapped in an expensive business model that isn't profitable.</p>
</div>
<hr>
<div class="warning-box">
	<p style="margin:4px 0;color: orange;"><strong>Outcome:</strong> The direct travel model isn't economically viable. Your transportation costs are eating most of the extra money you're earning. You're working hard but not getting ahead.</p>
</div>

