<div class="consequence-text">
	<p>You're caught in a trap: working hard, earning more gross income, but spending so much on transportation that your net income is barely higher than before. The "professional" direct service model sounded good, but the economics don't work. You need to find a different approach or accept that you're stuck on this expensive treadmill.</p>
</div>
<<link "Continue to day choice">><<goto "DayChoice">><</link>>

:: DirectTravelSuccess
<<set $step = 0>><<ShowInfo>><<set $day += 60>><<GenerateTimeSkipWorries 60>>

<h3>Premium Service, Real Results</h3>
<div class="consequence-text">
	<p>Five months of direct travel service. Five months of ridesharing across the city. Five months of significant transportation costs.</p>
	<p>But it's paying off.</p>
	<p>The referrals haven't just continued - they've accelerated. Satisfied clients tell their friends, family, neighbors. "I know someone," they say. "Professional, reliable, comes right to you."</p>
	<p>And crucially, you've learned to charge appropriately. Early on, you were charging the same rates as workers who couldn't travel. Now you know your service is worth more, and you've adjusted your prices:</p>
	<ul style="margin:8px 0;">
		<li>Basic repair job: $120 (was $80)</li>
		<li>Full day painting: $250 (was $180)</li>
		<li>Complex carpentry: $300+ (was $220)</li>
	</ul>
	<p>Clients accept these rates because of the convenience. They're not paying for just labor - they're paying for the fact that you show up at their door, professionally, with all tools, ready to work. No coordination needed on their part.</p>
	<p>Your daily earnings have increased to $220-280, even after rideshare costs of $80-100. You're netting $140-180 per day instead of the $95 you feared.</p>
	<p>More importantly, you've built a client base. People call you directly now, not through job coordinators. You have regulars who use you for all their home maintenance. They tip generously. They feed you lunch. They recommend you to everyone they know.</p>
	<p>After five months, you count your savings and realize you have enough for a car - and then some. A decent used vehicle costs around $1,600.</p>
</div>
<hr>

