:: DirectTravelCarShare
<<set $step = 0>><<ShowInfo>>

<h3>Shared Opportunity</h3>
<div class="consequence-text">
	<p>You could easily afford to buy the car alone, but something makes you pause. You remember how hard it was to get here. How many times you almost gave up. How much you relied on the support of others.</p>
	<p>You reach out to your network from the shelter. There's another family - from Honduras this time - who's been struggling with the same transportation challenges. They've been saving but haven't reached $1,600 yet. They have about $800.</p>
	<p>You meet them at a restaurant. "I have a proposal," you tell them. "Let's buy a car together. We split the cost, split the usage. You get transportation now instead of waiting months. I get to keep more of my savings for my business."</p>
	<p>The husband is skeptical at first. "Why would you do this? You can afford your own car."</p>
	<p>"Because someone helped me when I needed it," you say. "Now I can help you."</p>
	<p>You work out the details: schedules, maintenance, insurance. It's more complicated than owning alone, but it's worth it. Together, you buy a 2010 Toyota Corolla for $1,600. You each pay $800, plus half the insurance and registration.</p>
	<p>Your wife understands immediately when you tell her. "This is how we survived," she says. "By helping each other."</p>
	<p>The other family becomes more than car co-owners. They become trusted friends, part of your support network. When you need help, they're there. When they need help, you're there.</p>
</div>
<hr>
<div class="success-box">
	<p style="color: green;"><strong>Success:</strong> You co-own a car while maintaining significant savings for your business. You've built a strong community connection and helped another family access opportunity they couldn't reach alone.</p>
</div>

